programme.title: Breakfast
programme.desc: Naga Munchetty and Charlie Stayt present a round-up of national and international news, plus current affairs, arts and entertainment, and weather.

programme.title: Rip Off Britain: Holidays
programme.desc: The team hears from a short-term rental customer unexpectedly thrown out of the New York apartment they had booked. Plus, the website taking bookings for a non-existent hotel.

programme.title: Homes Under the Hammer
programme.desc: Martin Roberts looks over two houses - one in Wimbledon and another in Birmingham - and Dion Dublin meets the buyers of a semi-detached in Bootle, Merseyside.

programme.title: Wanted Down Under
programme.desc: Lynne Donnelly wants to move to Australia, so she takes her family for a trial week in Melbourne in the hope of convincing them to leave their home in Scotland for good.

programme.title: Caught Red Handed
programme.desc: A prolific burglar targets businesses including a pizza shop, a pub and a chippy. Plus, an elderly man's home is broken into, and watches of great sentimental value are taken.

programme.title: Bargain Hunt
programme.desc: Antiques experts Christina Trevanion and Kate Bateman help two teams search for items at Kent County Showground in Detling, with the Reds featuring the show's oldest participant.

programme.title: Doctors
programme.desc: Mrs Tembe delivers a talk at the church, but struggles with her young audience. Al extends a hand of friendship to Daniel, while Rob faces an internal investigation after a serious allegation is made. He insists he has done nothing wrong, but can he prove his innocence?

programme.title: Father Brown
programme.desc: The Kembleford Ramblers' annual outing takes a tragic turn when the local lord is found strangled, so the cleric gets his walking boots on to solve the crime. Murder mystery, starring Mark Williams.

programme.title: I Escaped to the Country
programme.desc: In the Welsh Border region, Alistair Appleton is reunited with a house-hunting couple who originally had a £475,000 budget and serious ambitions to start a smallholding. Within just a few years of moving into one of the properties Alistair showed them, they've not only transformed parts of their new home, but are also making impressive strides towards self-sufficiency on their land. Whilst in the region, Alistair also takes in the countryside and heritage of the Welshpool and Llanfair Light Railway.

programme.title: The Farmers' Country Showdown
programme.desc: Shrewsbury Food Festival plays host to first-generation farmer Sam, with his rare breed of pork, and the family run Kerry Vale Vineyard, selling their English wine.

programme.title: Antiques Road Trip
programme.desc: Natasha Raskin Sharp and Philip Serrell visit the antiques shops of Yorkshire, along the way meeting a trombone-maker and discovering the history of the rocking horse.

programme.title: Pointless
programme.desc: Quiz in which contestants try to score the fewest points possible by giving the least obvious correct answers to questions. Presented by Alexander Armstrong, with Richard Osman.

programme.title: The One Show
programme.desc: Matt Baker and Alex Jones present the live magazine show featuring a mixture of celebrity chat and stories of interest.

programme.title: EastEnders
programme.desc: With tensions still high between the Carters, Linda encourages Mick to explain what is going on, prompting him to finally open up about his time in prison. Dot confronts Stuart about the stolen photo and demands he leaves her house. Keanu braces himself for a difficult driving lesson with Louise.

programme.title: DIY SOS
programme.sub-title: DIY SOS: The Big Build: Mildenhall
programme.desc: In March 2015, football fan Simon Dobbin was at an away game when he was set upon by a gang of men in an unprovoked attack that left him brain damaged, paralysed and unable to walk and talk. After many months in hospital he is finally back at home in Mildenhall Suffolk, where he receives round-the-clock care from wife Nicole. But the family home is unfit for Simon's care and rehabilitation - so that's where Nick Knowles, designer Laurence Llewelyn- Bowen and the DIY SOS team come in, strengthened by a number of local tradesmen.

programme.title: Death in Paradise
programme.desc: DI Jack Mooney has a fresh mystery to solve when zoo owner Xander Shepherd is killed by a tranquilliser dart in the middle of the grounds. With the park shut to the public at the time, suspicion falls on the victim's colleagues - but given they were all in the staff area when the shot was fired, how could any of them have done the deed? Meanwhile, Dwayne's replacement arrives in the shape of new officer Ruby Patterson - who also happens to be the Commissioner's niece - and Jack faces a mammoth task when he is signed up to the island's charity swim race.

programme.title: Question Time
programme.desc: Fiona Bruce chairs the topical debate, inviting an audience in Derby to question a panel of politicians and other guests on issues of the day.

programme.title: This Week
programme.desc: Andrew Neil introduces a round-table chat, in which he, Michael Portillo and other guests take a look back at the past seven days' political and parliamentary developments.

programme.title: Breakfast
programme.desc: Charlie Stayt and Naga Munchetty present a round-up of national and international news, plus current affairs, arts and entertainment, and weather.

programme.title: Rip Off Britain: Holidays
programme.desc: The particular word on an air travel ticket that should ring alarm bells and the flight disruption that left one couple stranded for a week. Plus, the four-legged friend helping passengers with fear of flying.

programme.title: Homes Under the Hammer
programme.desc: Martel Maxwell visits properties in Birmingham and south Wales, while Dion Dublin is in Liverpool to see a place that has him confused.

programme.title: Wanted Down Under
programme.desc: Ciara McEleney wants to move her whole family to Australia for the better weather. Husband Ruairi, however, is proving to be a cloud on her new horizons. A week in Perth sees them check out the forecast for moving Down Under on a permanent basis. Presented by Nicki Chapman.

programme.title: Caught Red Handed
programme.desc: Dominic Littlewood reveals how police used ingenious methods to track down a robber who had attacked and injured a train enthusiast. Plus, the mechanic who used his technical know-how to bring crimes at a garage to a sudden stop.

programme.title: Bargain Hunt
programme.desc: Anita Manning hosts from Newmarket Racecourse, Suffolk, where two teams of best friends go head to head to maximise their returns, assisted by experts John Cameron and Caroline Hawley. Anita also learns about a legend of horse racing who didn't set foot on the turf.

programme.title: Doctors
programme.desc: Ruhma is overcome with emotion as she reminisces about Heston, while Mrs Tembe has something to confess that could jeopardise any plans she might have with Gordon. Elsewhere, Daniel and Zara almost put their troubled past to bed - but a stark reminder of someone threatens to destroy the moment.

programme.title: Father Brown
programme.desc: When Lady Felicia's home comes under threat, Father Brown is forced to seek help from an unlikely ally. Mark Williams and Nancy Carroll star. Last in the series.

programme.title: I Escaped to the Country
programme.desc: In Wiltshire, Jules Hudson revisits a fun-loving couple who have made radical changes to their property and transformed the garden not only to house their tortoises, but also a miniature tank `battleground'. He then catches up with a woman whose country home has allowed her to live the village `high life' and meets all her new friends at a garden croquet party. Last in the series.

programme.title: The Farmers' Country Showdown
programme.desc: Three passionate young farmers - the next generation of rising talent - battle it out at the Farmers Weekly Awards, to see who will be crowned Young Farmer of the Year. Narrated by Bill Paterson.

programme.title: Antiques Road Trip
programme.desc: Natasha Raskin Sharp and Philip Serrell scour the antiques shops around Sheffield to find something that will give them the edge at the auction. Natasha goes out of her comfort zone when considering some 18th-century pottery, but feels more at home when she spots something from the 1970s. Philip opts for some typically `Serrell' items, as well as chewing over more prehistoric stuff. He also goes out of his way to prove that chivalry isn't dead. On the road, Philip visits a factory using the world-famous Sheffield steel to make some very fine tools, and Natasha heads to the woods for a spot of foraging and some free food. It's going to be a nail biter at their final auction at Lytham St Annes, Lancashire.

programme.title: Pointless
programme.desc: Quiz in which contestants try to score the fewest points possible by giving the least obvious correct answers to questions. Presented by Alexander Armstrong, with Richard Osman.

programme.title: The One Show
programme.desc: Radio 1 breakfast show host Greg James joins regular host Alex Jones to explore the stories that matter from across the country.

programme.title: Celebrity Mastermind
programme.desc: Scissor Sisters singer Ana Matronic, The Inbetweeners star Joe Thomas, former rugby union player Maggie Alphonsi and restaurant critic Jay Rayner answer questions on the specialist subjects of The Bionic Woman, George Orwell, Denise Lewis and the film musicals of Arthur Freed. Host John Humphrys then puts their general knowledge to the test before winner is announced.

programme.title: EastEnders
programme.desc: It looks like the team are going to miss their match when the minibus fails to turn up, so Mick and Mitch come up with a Plan B to avoid the kids' disappointment. Dr Legg is pleased to hear that his parent's grave has been restored, Rainie makes the most of Max's attentiveness, and Louise and Keanu grow closer.

programme.title: A Question of Sport
programme.desc: Sue Barker asks the questions as athletics greats Roger Black and Sonia O'Sullivan team up with Phil Tufnell, and Matt Dawson is joined by former American football stars Jason Bell and Osi Umenyiora.

programme.title: Would I Lie to You
programme.desc: Documentary-maker and reigning Strictly champion Stacey Dooley, presenter Alex Jones, comedian and musician Rachel Parris and stand-up comic Henning Wehn join host Rob Brydon and regular captains David Mitchell and Lee Mack on the comedy panel show. As ever, the participants aim to hoodwink their opponents with absurd facts and plausible lies about themselves in a bid to secure a team victory.

programme.title: Mrs Brown's Boys
programme.desc: Agnes needs someone to look after Grandad so she can treat herself to a much-needed holiday - but with private nursing homes being so expensive, it seems her only option is to convince the health visitor he has lost his marbles. Rory and Dino move in for a couple of weeks, and the matriarch is soon spitting feathers when the latter begins taking over the house, and her late husband gets in touch from beyond the grave with some ominous news. Hit comedy, starring Brendan O'Carroll.

programme.title: The Graham Norton Show
programme.desc: The host welcomes triple Oscar-nominated Laura Linney, who is returning to the London stage in the critically acclaimed My Name Is Lucy Barton. Actress Saoirse Ronan talks about playing the title role in new movie Mary Queen of Scots, whole rising star Timothee Chalamet discusses his powerful addiction drama Beautiful Boy. Plus, another bunch of intrepid audience members steps up to the plate, willing to recount an anecdote from the dreaded red chair.

programme.title: Cuckoo
programme.desc: Ivy, who has been spending some quality time with Dylan, discovers he has been running a weed farm in one of the properties he's supposedly selling. Meanwhile, Ken tries to make it up to Lorna after saying she is `only' an estate agent. Greg Davies, Andie MacDowell and Helen Baxendale star.

programme.title: The Double
programme.desc: A retired CIA agent returns to duty when a senator is murdered. The former spy believes the killing has all the hallmarks of an infamous Soviet assassin he spent most of his career in pursuit of, and joins forces with the inexperienced FBI agent assigned to the case. Espionage thriller, starring Richard Gere, Topher Grace and Martin Sheen.

programme.title: Breakfast
programme.desc: Charlie Stayt and Naga Munchetty present national and international news, plus sports reports, weather forecasts and arts and entertainment features. Including NewsWatch at 7.45.(n)

programme.title: Saturday Kitchen Live
programme.desc: Michel Roux Jr is joined by chefs Anna Jones and James Tanner, and special guest Brenda Blethyn, while Olly Smith selects the wines to go with the studio dishes.(n)

programme.title: Tom Kerridge's Fresh Start
programme.desc: Tom demonstrates ways that the whole family can help out cooking in the kitchen, and shares family favourite recipe ideas that are healthy and easy to prepare. First, Tom and his son Acey make filo pastry triangles with feta cheese, before he drops by to teach ten-year-old Nihirika and seven year-old Krish how to cook simple Asian-style glazed chicken thighs in their family home.(n)

programme.title: Football Focus
programme.desc: Dan Walker and guests review the week's headlines and look ahead to forthcoming fixtures, including Arsenal v Chelsea and Liverpool v Crystal Palace in the Premier League.(n)

programme.title: Live Snooker: The Masters
programme.desc: Coverage of the opening semi-final, played over the best of 11 frames on day seven at Alexandra Palace in London. At the corresponding stage of last year's tournament, eventual winner Mark Allen overcame John Higgins 6-3 to book his place in the showpiece match, where he would face Englishman Kyren Wilson. Coverage continues on BBC2.(n)

programme.title: Final Score
programme.desc: Jason Mohammad presents a round-up of the classified results and this afternoon's news from the Premier League, EFL and Scotland.(n)

programme.title: The Time It Takes
programme.desc: Joe Lycett and Alison Hammond host the game show, in which contestants face challenges including covering a person in wrapping paper and mopping up gravy using a flannel.(n)

programme.title: Pointless Celebrities
programme.desc: Alexander Armstrong and Richard Osman present a writers special edition of the general knowledge quiz. Contestants are Richard Madeley, Dreda Say Mitchell, John O'Farrell, Lise Mayer, Jenny Colgan, Jane Fallon, Richard Stilgoe and Don Black.(n)

programme.title: Michael McIntyre's Big Show
programme.desc: The host looks back over his favourite surprises and pranks from the last four series of his Big Show. Ed Balls, Alexander Armstrong and Carol Vorderman talk about what it was like to hand over their phone in Celebrity Send to All, while Gino D'Acampo relives what it was like waking up and finding Michael in his bedroom on Midnight Gameshow. Closing the show will be unexpected star Anush Hydros, who is now starring on the West End stage.(n)

programme.title: The Greatest Dancer
programme.desc: Alesha Dixon and Jordan Banjo host the dancing contest, featuring performers from a variety of styles, including ballet, jazz, street, ballroom, contemporary and disco, competing for a £50,000 prize and the chance to showcase their skills on the next series of Strictly Come Dancing. Cheryl, Matthew Morrison and Oti Mabuse are on hand to help the competitors make the best use of their talents - but which contestants get to go through the show's magic mirror and make it through to the next round is entirely in the hands of the studio audience.(n)

programme.title: Casualty
programme.desc: Alicia finds out that she has been offered a place on a coveted paediatric fellowship in Manchester, forcing her to make a decision on her future. Elsewhere, Marty's lies begin to catch up with him, while Elle is disappointed when she has to hand back to reins as clinical lead to a returning Connie.(n)

programme.title: Match of the Day
programme.desc: Gary Lineker presents highlights of the latest Premier League matches, including Arsenal v Chelsea at the Emirates Stadium and Liverpool v Crystal Palace at Anfield. Both league fixtures between the Gunners and the Blues last season ended in draws, including a 2-2 result on this ground. However, Maurizio Sarri's side overcame Unai Emery's men 3-2 in this season's reverse fixture at Stamford Bridge, thanks to goals from Pedro, Alvaro Morata and Marcos Alonso. Plus, action from Bournemouth v West Ham United at the Vitality Stadium, Manchester United v Brighton & Hove Albion at Old Trafford, Newcastle United v Cardiff City at St James' Park, Southampton v Everton at St Mary's Stadium, Watford v Burnley at Vicarage Road and Wolverhampton Wanderers v Leicester City at Molineux.(n)

programme.title: The NFL Show
programme.desc: Mark Chapman looks ahead to the Conference Championship games, joined by former NFL stars Osi Umenyiora and Jason Bell.(n)

programme.title: Live Snooker: The Masters
programme.desc: Coverage of the opening semi-final, played over the best of 11 frames on day seven at Alexandra Palace in London. At the corresponding stage of last year's tournament, eventual winner Mark Allen overcame John Higgins 6-3 to book his place in the showpiece match, where he would face Englishman Kyren Wilson. Coverage continues on BBC2.(n)

programme.title: Final Score
programme.desc: Jason Mohammad presents a round-up of the classified results and this afternoon's news from the Premier League, EFL and Scotland.(n)

programme.title: The Time It Takes
programme.desc: Joe Lycett and Alison Hammond host the game show, in which contestants face challenges including covering a person in wrapping paper and mopping up gravy using a flannel.(n)

programme.title: Pointless Celebrities
programme.desc: Alexander Armstrong and Richard Osman present a writers special edition of the general knowledge quiz. Contestants are Richard Madeley, Dreda Say Mitchell, John O'Farrell, Lise Mayer, Jenny Colgan, Jane Fallon, Richard Stilgoe and Don Black.(n)

programme.title: Michael McIntyre's Big Show
programme.desc: The host looks back over his favourite surprises and pranks from the last four series of his Big Show. Ed Balls, Alexander Armstrong and Carol Vorderman talk about what it was like to hand over their phone in Celebrity Send to All, while Gino D'Acampo relives what it was like waking up and finding Michael in his bedroom on Midnight Gameshow. Closing the show will be unexpected star Anush Hydros, who is now starring on the West End stage.(n)

programme.title: The Greatest Dancer
programme.desc: Alesha Dixon and Jordan Banjo host the dancing contest, featuring performers from a variety of styles, including ballet, jazz, street, ballroom, contemporary and disco, competing for a £50,000 prize and the chance to showcase their skills on the next series of Strictly Come Dancing. Cheryl, Matthew Morrison and Oti Mabuse are on hand to help the competitors make the best use of their talents - but which contestants get to go through the show's magic mirror and make it through to the next round is entirely in the hands of the studio audience.(n)

programme.title: Casualty
programme.desc: Alicia finds out that she has been offered a place on a coveted paediatric fellowship in Manchester, forcing her to make a decision on her future. Elsewhere, Marty's lies begin to catch up with him, while Elle is disappointed when she has to hand back to reins as clinical lead to a returning Connie.(n)

programme.title: Match of the Day
programme.desc: Gary Lineker presents highlights of the latest Premier League matches, including Arsenal v Chelsea at the Emirates Stadium and Liverpool v Crystal Palace at Anfield. Both league fixtures between the Gunners and the Blues last season ended in draws, including a 2-2 result on this ground. However, Maurizio Sarri's side overcame Unai Emery's men 3-2 in this season's reverse fixture at Stamford Bridge, thanks to goals from Pedro, Alvaro Morata and Marcos Alonso. Plus, action from Bournemouth v West Ham United at the Vitality Stadium, Manchester United v Brighton & Hove Albion at Old Trafford, Newcastle United v Cardiff City at St James' Park, Southampton v Everton at St Mary's Stadium, Watford v Burnley at Vicarage Road and Wolverhampton Wanderers v Leicester City at Molineux.(n)

programme.title: The NFL Show
programme.desc: Mark Chapman looks ahead to the Conference Championship games, joined by former NFL stars Osi Umenyiora and Jason Bell.(n)

programme.title: Snooker: The Masters - Extra
programme.desc: Judd Trump v Kyren Wilson. Extended highlights of the first-round match on the fourth day at Alexandra Palace in London.

programme.title: See Hear
programme.sub-title: See Hear on Tour: Tel Aviv
programme.desc: Nadeem Islam visits Tel Aviv to see what it has to offer deaf tourists. With voiceover.

programme.title: Cities: Nature's New Wild
programme.desc: Footage of animals that have made their homes in urban environments around the world. Featuring huge colonies of bats in Adelaide, smooth-coated otters at home in Singapore, and reticulated pythons living on the streets of Bangkok. Narrated by Daniel Kaluuya.

programme.title: The Farmers' Country Showdown
programme.desc: New series. The return of the programme celebrating inspirational farming families and the rural events where they showcase their hard work. Beekeeper Valentine and market gardener John meet their regular customers and discover new ones selling their skincare products and organic vegetables at St George's weekly market in central Belfast.

programme.desc: The Parker family spend a trial week living in Melbourne, Australia, but wife Mandy is not convinced the move would be the best decision for their son, who has special needs.

programme.title: The Farmers' Country Showdown
programme.desc: Veterinary surgeon Robin goes head to head with 81-year-old breeder Di in the National Competition at the Royal Norfolk Show, showcasing their diminutive Dexter cattle.

programme.title: MasterChef: The Professionals
programme.desc: The first three remaining semi-finalists compete for a place in Finals Week, and are sent to work alongside one of the country's leading chefs, Michael Caines. The contestants are challenged to cook one of his signature dishes, before joining his staff during a packed service in his prestigious restaurant. Finally, they return to the MasterChef kitchen to prepare a menu for the judges.

programme.desc: Coverage of the first quarter-final on day five from Alexandra Palace in London, as John Higgins or Ryan Day face Ronnie O'Sullivan or Stuart Bingham. O'Sullivan lost his first match in this tournament since 2015 at this stage last year when he was thrashed 6-1 by eventual champion Mark Allen.

programme.title: Coast
programme.desc: Nick Crane investigates the formation of Ireland's Clew Bay when the landscape was covered in ice, and Alice Roberts unearths the remains of the oldest farm in the British Isles. Plus, Neil Oliver discovers how a 16th-century so-called pirate queen turned her coastal home into an impregnable fortress.

programme.title: Flog It
programme.desc: A collection of interesting finds from around the country, including visits to the Ulster Transport Museum and Bletchley Park. Paul Martin also uncovers the story of the shipwrecked Metta Catharina in Cornwall.

programme.title: Eggheads
programme.desc: Jeremy Vine hosts the quiz in which the winners of famous game shows work as a team to tackle a new set of challengers hoping to win a cash prize.

programme.title: Great Alaskan and Canadian Railroad Journeys
programme.sub-title: Great Canadian Railway Journeys: Miramichi to Quebec City
programme.desc: Michael Portillo starts the next leg of his journey in the Acadian fishing village of Neguac, New Brunswick, where he learns how to farm sea oysters, before investigating why the French-speaking Acadians were expelled by the British from lands they had occupied further south. Boarding the night sleeper for the next 400 miles, he heads for Quebec City. With its narrow streets and flights of steps, and a hotel modelled on a 16th-century chateau, the city was the heart of New France and reminds Michael of Paris. However, its national dish leaves him cold.

programme.title: Politics Live
programme.desc: In the week of Parliament's vote on the Prime Minister's Brexit deal, a special edition of Politics Live with all the latest news and analysis from Westminster.

programme.title: Back in Time for School
programme.desc: The time-travelling documentary reaches the post-Second World War years, when a revolution in education saw children separated into one of three schools - grammars, secondary moderns and technical. The volunteer pupils attend grammar, representing the one in four children who won a coveted place by passing the 11-plus exam. Here, they delve into teachings on sex education, cycling proficiency, the Coronation of Queen Elizabeth II in 1953 and rising incomes in the mid-1950s as well as debates among boys and girls on fighting for your country.

programme.title: Hospital
programme.desc: The documentary focuses on the staff and patients of the Walton Centre, the UK's only dedicated spine, brain and pain management centre, which sits adjacent to Aintree University Hospital. Among the patients are 22-year-old Sophie, who suffered serious inflammation of the brain stem which means she has to be on a ventilator at night, and Tom, 18, who sustained significant head injuries in a car crash and now struggles to remember the simplest of things. For further rehabilitation, however, he will need private rehabilitation services, and that will require funding.

programme.title: Better Things
programme.desc: Sam hopes that she can no longer get pregnant, then has to handle her daughters' escalating bad behaviour and her mother's heightened eccentricity.

programme.title: The Archiveologists
programme.desc: Comedians Diane Morgan and Joe Wilkinson parody archive documentaries from the 1960s, examining what telecommunications in the 1990s might be like.

programme.title: Newsnight
programme.desc: Analysis of the day's events, presented by Kirsty Wark.

programme.title: Snooker: The Masters
programme.desc: Action from the second quarter-final on day five from Alexandra Palace in London, as Mark Allen or Luca Brecel faced Ding Junhui or Jack Lisowski.

programme.title: Snooker: The Masters - Extra
programme.desc: Extended highlights of the first quarter-final on day five from Alexandra Palace in London, as John Higgins or Ryan Day faced Ronnie O'Sullivan or Stuart Bingham.

programme.title: Britain's Fat Fight with Hugh Fearnley-Whittingstall
programme.sub-title: Britain's Fat Fight: The Battle Continues
programme.desc: Britain is already the fattest country in Western Europe and if trends continue, more than 50 per cent will be obese by 2050. Last year, Hugh Fearnley-Whittingstall presented a three-part documentary in which he set out to tackle the national obesity crisis. Now he returns with a final instalment, examining some of the misleading marketing claims on `healthier' products, unveiling the truth about why Brits love to snack and challenging a family to rethink their portion sizes. He also heads to Westminster with Jamie Oliver to talk to MPs about the obesity crisis and gets an opportunity to put his questions directly to the Health Minister.

programme.title: Back in Time for School
programme.desc: Fifteen teenagers and three teachers embark on a time-travelling adventure through 100 years of school history. Led by presenter Sara Cox and social historian Polly Russell, the volunteers fast-forward through seven different eras, taking them to the end of the 20th century - and in each period there will be new school dinners to try, new trips to take and new ideas about what school is actually for. They begin in Victorian times, where they discover what it was like for the lucky four per cent of children able to attend school at a time when education was still seen as a preserve for the rich but a handful of schools offered affordable places to ordinary families for the first time.

programme.title: Trust Me, I'm a Doctor
programme.desc: Michael Mosley tests whether Tai Chi is as good for our health as vigorous exercise, and Dr Giles Yeo asks what can be done to treat heartburn. Elsewhere, Surgeon Gabriel Weston discovers a pioneering new technology that's transforming complex brain surgery, and Dr Zoe Williams asks how safe are the medicines we buy online are.

programme.title: This Is BBC Two
programme.desc: Preview of upcoming programmes from BBC Two.

programme.title: Wanted Down Under
programme.desc: Lynne Donnelly wants to move to Australia, so she takes her family for a trial week in Melbourne in the hope of convincing them to leave their home in Scotland for good.

programme.title: The Farmers' Country Showdown
programme.desc: Shrewsbury Food Festival plays host to first-generation farmer Sam, with his rare breed of pork, and the family run Kerry Vale Vineyard, selling their English wine.

programme.title: Antiques Roadshow
programme.desc: Fiona Bruce looks back at favourite finds from the past 40 years of the programme, while a selection of experts reveal what happened next to some memorable items. Ronnie Archer-Morgan revisits his emotional encounter with a set of Sooty and Sweep puppets and explains how it rekindled memories of a long-lost friend from his time in a children's home, while Fiona hears how a ring featured on the show inspired a romantic proposal.

programme.title: Politics Live
programme.desc: Jo Coburn presents the big political issues of the day from Westminster and beyond.

programme.title: Live Snooker: The Masters
programme.desc: Coverage of the third quarter-final on day six from Alexandra Palace in London, featuring Mark Selby or Stephen Maguire v Judd Trump or Kyren Wilson. Trump and Wilson were among the victorious quarter-finalists last year, overcoming Shaun Murphy and Mark Williams respectively.

programme.title: Coast
programme.sub-title: Glasgow to Edinburgh via Caledonian Canal
programme.desc: The team explores the Caledonian Canal. Neil Oliver gets aboard the Clyde Puffer, the last working coal-fired, steam-powered cargo vessel of its kind, Alice Roberts investigates the life of painter Joan Eardley in Catterline, and Nick Crane reveals how the canals that link the lochs of the Great Glen fault were created. Miranda Krestovnikoff finds out about a tunnel network created by worms at Loch Creran, Hermione Cockburn visits the islands around Easdale, and Mark Horton examines the history of the Picts in Burghead.

programme.title: Flog It
programme.desc: Paul Martin presents from Crowcombe Court in Somerset, where he is joined by experts James Lewis and Thomas Plant. James' knowledge of Derby porcelain is tested and Thomas discovers an amber necklace that was washed up on a local beach. Plus, Paul has a go on a locally made device known as a mud-horse, which is designed to help fishermen skim over the mud flats to get to and from their nets.

programme.title: Eggheads
programme.desc: Jeremy Vine hosts the quiz in which the winners of famous game shows work as a team to tackle a new set of challengers hoping to win a cash prize.

programme.title: Great Alaskan and Canadian Railroad Journeys
programme.sub-title: Great Canadian Railway Journeys: Saint-Anne de Beaupre to La Malbaie
programme.desc: Michael Portillo explores the Province of Quebec, taking the scenic Train de Charlevoix along the north bank of the mighty St Lawrence River to La Malbaie. Michael tours the 19th-century houses, once the haunt of the Gatsby generation, before taking to the skies flying over the Laurentian Mountains to land on an isolated lake where he fishes for trout. At Baie St Paul, Michael discovers a farm producing wines of sufficient calibre to be served at the G7 conference, while the waterfall at Montmorency proves a spectacular sight - especially from a zip wire.

programme.title: Live Snooker: The Masters
programme.desc: Coverage of the fourth quarter-final on day six from Alexandra Palace in London, featuring Barry Hawkins or Shaun Murphy v Mark Williams or Neil Robertson. Perhaps surprisingly, none of the four players potentially involved this evening made it beyond this stage in 2018.

programme.title: Mastermind
programme.desc: John Humphrys invites four contestants to answer questions on their specialist topics of theoretical physicist Albert Einstein, MC Beaton's Hamish Macbeth novels, gardener, architect and MP Sir Joseph Paxton and the Egyptian pharaoh Akhenaten. They are then each afforded two minutes to demonstrate their general knowledge.

programme.title: Grand Tours of Scotland's Lochs
programme.desc: Paul Murton heads to Altnabreac, one of Britain's remotest railway stations, which was built to service several grand sporting lodges in the days when the rich and fashionable came to shoot game and fish the lochs of the Caithness and Sutherland peatlands. He then joins up with local Yvonne Creedy to pan for gold in an icy river before heading to the sacred spring of Loch ma Naire. Paul ends his journey on the sands of the Kyle of Tongue, where he learns about a consignment of Jacobite gold that could have changed history.

programme.title: The Victorian House of Arts and Crafts
programme.desc: Using original tools and techniques, the six 21st-century crafters are set to make from scratch a Victorian double bed and bed spread, a bedside clock and plaster-wall decoration in a week, all the while eating, working and living within the philosophies first outlined by the likes of John Ruskin and William Morris. Will their 1890s communal life help them to better understand the depth and scale of the arts and crafts movement, both as a power for artistic and social change? Once again, host Anita Rani is joined by contributors Keith Brymer Jones and Patch Rogers.

programme.title: QI
programme.desc: Phill Jupitus, Cally Beaton and Rhod Gilbert join regular panellist Alan Davies and host Sandi Toksvig for an unconventional look at a potpourri of topics, while facing some impossible questions. As ever, correctness and even intelligence go out of the window, as the fiendishly difficult questions lead to points being awarded for the answers its questionmaster finds most interesting, as opposed to correct.

programme.title: Newsnight
programme.desc: Analysis of the day's events, presented by Mark Urban.

programme.title: Front Row Late
programme.desc: As a new exhibition of work by Victorian artist and critic John Ruskin opens in London, Mary Beard and guests David Olusoga, Shahidha Bari and Simon Jenkins discuss whether we can ever agree on the meaning of beauty, or whether it truly is in the eye of the beholder.

programme.title: Snooker: The Masters
programme.desc: Action from the fourth quarter-final on day six from Alexandra Palace in London, featuring Barry Hawkins or Shaun Murphy v Mark Williams or Neil Robertson.

programme.title: Snooker: The Masters - Extra
programme.desc: Extended highlights of the third quarter-final on day six from Alexandra Palace in London, featuring Mark Selby or Stephen Maguire v Judd Trump or Kyren Wilson.(n)

programme.title: Panorama
programme.desc: The UK fast-food industry is booming, with UK consumers spending more than £10 billion a year on takeaway food, with the online market being dominated by giants like JustEat and Deliveroo. But what is the real cost of convenience? Tina Daheley lifts the lid on its secrets, revealing how planning laws are being subverted and food safety legislation flouted in the battle to secure custom.(n)

programme.title: Imagine
programme.sub-title: Imagine - Tracey Emin: Where Do You Draw the Line?
programme.desc: Alan Yentob follows the artist over the course of the last year to chart her creative process at work, and talks about her life to date and how she sees the rest of her career. Tracey discusses her troubled early years in Margate and the series of breakthroughs in the 1990s that saw her become a leading light of the Young British Artists, featuring career-defining work like My Bed and her embroidered tent Everyone I Have Ever Slept With 1963-1995. Contributors include Sir Nicholas Serota, Jay Jopling, Maria Balshaw and David Dawson.(n)

programme.title: This Is BBC Two
programme.desc: Preview of upcoming programmes from BBC Two.(n)

programme.title: All Over the Place: Asia
programme.desc: Featuring a Korean rocket festival and solar-powered supertrees in Singapore.(n)

programme.title: Wild & Weird
programme.desc: Naomi Wilkinson and Tim Warwood investigate odd auditory occurrences, including a man who collects worms by grunting, and a gang of prairie dogs doing a Mexican wave.(n)

programme.title: All Over the Workplace
programme.desc: Freya sees herself as a full-time professional footballer and Chitua wants to be a player before progressing to manager. They visit a professional football club where they are put through their paces by the coaches, then meet the manager to find out all about formations and tactics. Presented by Alex Riley.(n)

programme.title: Show Me What You're Made Of
programme.desc: Stacey Dooley presents as the five kids return to the south of England for a taste of some of the shift work done at night by thousands of people across the country. The kids are taken aback to discover that they are joining the cleaning team at a big bus garage in south London. It's hard physical work, and the shift goes on long into the night, requiring them to sweep, mop and wash each double-decker bus by hand. As the job goes on, the youngsters are shocked to discover what passengers have left behind for them to clean up.(n)

programme.title: The Dog Ate My Homework
programme.desc: Host Iain Stirling is joined by child team captains Joseph and Aqos and special guests Sam Nixon, Mark Rhodes, Charlie Baker and Yuriko Kotani who battle it out in a series of hilarious rounds and challenges.(n)

programme.title: Richard Hammond's Invisible Worlds
programme.desc: The Top Gear presenter concludes his investigation, revealing a miniature universe of activity lying just beyond the limits of the human eye. He learns how the gecko lizard is capable of defying gravity, and demonstrates how microscopic changes in ice crystals can cause devastating avalanches. Plus, he explores the infectious range of a sneeze.(n)

programme.title: Natural World
programme.desc: Award-winning writer Robert Macfarlane spends a year travelling around Essex to discover the variety of landscapes and wildlife in the county. During his journey he visits desolate beaches and wild woods, sees huge flocks of red knot over the Thames, and encounters an array of animals including peregrine falcons, water voles, deer, barn owls and seals.(n)

programme.title: Homes Under the Hammer
programme.desc: Martin Roberts, Martel Maxwell and Dion Dublin follow the progress of a three-bedroom flat in Epsom, Surrey, a Wolverhampton house and a bungalow in the Cornish village of Ashton.(n)

programme.title: Food & Drink
programme.desc: Chef Gennaro Contaldo joins Michel Roux Jr in the kitchen to create an authentic lasagne with focaccia from scratch, while Kate Goodman offers a guide to choosing the right Italian red wine to make the perfect match. Great British Menu judge and restaurateur Oliver Peyton joins them for a debate on whether people should care more about where their food comes from.(n)

programme.title: Best Bakes Ever
programme.desc: In light of Britain's baking obsession, actress and cake expert Jane Asher presents a selection of recipes from television chefs, including James Martin, Mary Berry, Paul Hollywood, the Hairy Bikers, Raymond Blanc, Nigella Lawson, Tom Kerridge, Lorraine Pascale and Rachel Khoo.(n)

programme.title: Money for Nothing
programme.desc: Sarah Moore and her team revamp a pair of brown atomic chairs with the help of upholsterer Anthony Devine, and later find a mid-century hall unit that needs bringing up to date.(n)

programme.title: Back in Time for School
programme.desc: The time-travelling documentary reaches the post-Second World War years, when a revolution in education saw children separated into one of three schools - grammars, secondary moderns and technical. The volunteer pupils attend grammar, representing the one in four children who won a coveted place by passing the 11-plus exam. Here, they delve into teachings on sex education, cycling proficiency, the Coronation of Queen Elizabeth II in 1953 and rising incomes in the mid-1950s as well as debates among boys and girls on fighting for your country.(n)

programme.title: Tennis: Australian Open
programme.sub-title: Tennis: Australian Open Highlights: 2019 Day Six
programme.desc: Kat Downes presents action from day six of the opening Grand Slam tournament of the year, which takes place at Melbourne Park, and featured the latest third-round matches. Eventual men's singles champion Roger Federer sailed through to the last 16 with a straight-sets victory over Richard Gasquet at this stage last year, but women's top seed Simona Halep survived a much tougher test, defeating Lauren Davis in a match that lasted a remarkable three hours and 45 minutes.(n)

programme.title: Live Snooker: The Masters
programme.desc: Further coverage of the opening semi-final, played over the best of 11 frames on day seven at Alexandra Palace in London. The victorious player will have the opportunity to win the first Triple Crown title of the year and a first prize of £200,000 in tomorrow's final.(n)

programme.title: Yorkshire Wolds Way with Paul Rose
programme.desc: Part two of two. Adventurer Paul Rose concludes his exploration of the 79-mile Yorkshire Wolds Way, taking to the skies to get a unique view of its stretch of chalk downland. He also receives a special invitation to a military base that has been keeping the nation safe since the start of the Second World War.(n)

programme.title: Cities: Nature's New Wild
programme.desc: Animals displaced from their habitats by human expansion, including elephants in Sri Lanka and capuchin monkeys on the Pacific coast of Costa Rica. The programme also examines situations where humans have learned to live alongside their animal neighbours, including a heron that has been visiting an Amsterdam house twice a day for 17 years and a project to preserve manatees in Florida that has saved them from being an endangered species. Last in the series.(n)

programme.title: Live Snooker: The Masters
programme.desc: Coverage of the second semi-final, played over the best of 11 frames on day seven at Alexandra Palace in London. Despite being an invitational event, this tournament is considered one of the more prestigious on the snooker calendar, and with the winner set to claim a cheque for £200,000, both of the players in this contest will be eager to progress to tomorrow's final. Kyren Wilson produced one of the most memorable comebacks in Masters history at this stage last year, overcoming a 5-2 deficit against Judd Trump to prevail 6-5 and become the first player born in the 1990s to reach a Triple Crown final. Though defeating Mark Allen in the final proved to be a bridge too far, Wilson has gone from strength to strength since his run here, establishing himself in the world's top 10.(n)

programme.title: Stockholm, My Love
programme.desc: Premiere. A Swedish architect travels through Stockholm on a journey of recovery to find peace and understanding from something bad that happened to her exactly a year earlier. Drama, starring Neneh Cherry, marking the fiction debut for director Mark Cousins.(n)

programme.title: Britain's Fat Fight with Hugh Fearnley-Whittingstall
programme.sub-title: Britain's Fat Fight: The Battle Continues
programme.desc: Britain is already the fattest country in Western Europe and if trends continue, more than 50 per cent will be obese by 2050. Last year, Hugh Fearnley-Whittingstall presented a three-part documentary in which he set out to tackle the national obesity crisis. Now he returns with a final instalment, examining some of the misleading marketing claims on `healthier' products, unveiling the truth about why Brits love to snack and challenging a family to rethink their portion sizes. He also heads to Westminster with Jamie Oliver to talk to MPs about the obesity crisis and gets an opportunity to put his questions directly to the Health Minister.

programme.title: Back in Time for School
programme.desc: Fifteen teenagers and three teachers embark on a time-travelling adventure through 100 years of school history. Led by presenter Sara Cox and social historian Polly Russell, the volunteers fast-forward through seven different eras, taking them to the end of the 20th century - and in each period there will be new school dinners to try, new trips to take and new ideas about what school is actually for. They begin in Victorian times, where they discover what it was like for the lucky four per cent of children able to attend school at a time when education was still seen as a preserve for the rich but a handful of schools offered affordable places to ordinary families for the first time.

programme.title: Trust Me, I'm a Doctor
programme.desc: Michael Mosley tests whether Tai Chi is as good for our health as vigorous exercise, and Dr Giles Yeo asks what can be done to treat heartburn. Elsewhere, Surgeon Gabriel Weston discovers a pioneering new technology that's transforming complex brain surgery, and Dr Zoe Williams asks how safe are the medicines we buy online are.

programme.title: Antiques Roadshow

programme.title: Live Snooker: The Masters
programme.desc: Coverage of the third quarter-final on day six from Alexandra Palace in London, featuring Mark Selby or Stephen Maguire v Judd Trump or Kyren Wilson. Trump and Wilson were among the victorious quarter-finalists last year, overcoming Shaun Murphy and Mark Williams respectively.

programme.title: Coast
programme.sub-title: Glasgow to Edinburgh via Caledonian Canal
programme.desc: The team explores the Caledonian Canal. Neil Oliver gets aboard the Clyde Puffer, the last working coal-fired, steam-powered cargo vessel of its kind, Alice Roberts investigates the life of painter Joan Eardley in Catterline, and Nick Crane reveals how the canals that link the lochs of the Great Glen fault were created. Miranda Krestovnikoff finds out about a tunnel network created by worms at Loch Creran, Hermione Cockburn visits the islands around Easdale, and Mark Horton examines the history of the Picts in Burghead.

programme.title: Flog It
programme.desc: Paul Martin presents from Crowcombe Court in Somerset, where he is joined by experts James Lewis and Thomas Plant. James' knowledge of Derby porcelain is tested and Thomas discovers an amber necklace that was washed up on a local beach. Plus, Paul has a go on a locally made device known as a mud-horse, which is designed to help fishermen skim over the mud flats to get to and from their nets.

programme.title: Eggheads
programme.desc: Jeremy Vine hosts the quiz in which the winners of famous game shows work as a team to tackle a new set of challengers hoping to win a cash prize.

programme.title: Great Alaskan and Canadian Railroad Journeys
programme.sub-title: Great Canadian Railway Journeys: Saint-Anne de Beaupre to La Malbaie
programme.desc: Michael Portillo explores the Province of Quebec, taking the scenic Train de Charlevoix along the north bank of the mighty St Lawrence River to La Malbaie. Michael tours the 19th-century houses, once the haunt of the Gatsby generation, before taking to the skies flying over the Laurentian Mountains to land on an isolated lake where he fishes for trout. At Baie St Paul, Michael discovers a farm producing wines of sufficient calibre to be served at the G7 conference, while the waterfall at Montmorency proves a spectacular sight - especially from a zip wire.

programme.title: Live Snooker: The Masters
programme.desc: Coverage of the fourth quarter-final on day six from Alexandra Palace in London, featuring Barry Hawkins or Shaun Murphy v Mark Williams or Neil Robertson. Perhaps surprisingly, none of the four players potentially involved this evening made it beyond this stage in 2018.

programme.title: Mastermind
programme.desc: John Humphrys invites four contestants to answer questions on their specialist topics of theoretical physicist Albert Einstein, MC Beaton's Hamish Macbeth novels, gardener, architect and MP Sir Joseph Paxton and the Egyptian pharaoh Akhenaten. They are then each afforded two minutes to demonstrate their general knowledge.

programme.title: Grand Tours of Scotland's Lochs
programme.desc: Paul Murton heads to Altnabreac, one of Britain's remotest railway stations, which was built to service several grand sporting lodges in the days when the rich and fashionable came to shoot game and fish the lochs of the Caithness and Sutherland peatlands. He then joins up with local Yvonne Creedy to pan for gold in an icy river before heading to the sacred spring of Loch ma Naire. Paul ends his journey on the sands of the Kyle of Tongue, where he learns about a consignment of Jacobite gold that could have changed history.

programme.title: The Victorian House of Arts and Crafts
programme.desc: Using original tools and techniques, the six 21st-century crafters are set to make from scratch a Victorian double bed and bed spread, a bedside clock and plaster-wall decoration in a week, all the while eating, working and living within the philosophies first outlined by the likes of John Ruskin and William Morris. Will their 1890s communal life help them to better understand the depth and scale of the arts and crafts movement, both as a power for artistic and social change? Once again, host Anita Rani is joined by contributors Keith Brymer Jones and Patch Rogers.

programme.title: QI
programme.desc: Phill Jupitus, Cally Beaton and Rhod Gilbert join regular panellist Alan Davies and host Sandi Toksvig for an unconventional look at a potpourri of topics, while facing some impossible questions. As ever, correctness and even intelligence go out of the window, as the fiendishly difficult questions lead to points being awarded for the answers its questionmaster finds most interesting, as opposed to correct.

programme.title: Newsnight
programme.desc: Analysis of the day's events, presented by Mark Urban.

programme.title: Front Row Late
programme.desc: As a new exhibition of work by Victorian artist and critic John Ruskin opens in London, Mary Beard and guests David Olusoga, Shahidha Bari and Simon Jenkins discuss whether we can ever agree on the meaning of beauty, or whether it truly is in the eye of the beholder.

programme.title: Snooker: The Masters
programme.desc: Action from the fourth quarter-final on day six from Alexandra Palace in London, featuring Barry Hawkins or Shaun Murphy v Mark Williams or Neil Robertson.

programme.desc: Extended highlights of the third quarter-final on day six from Alexandra Palace in London, featuring Mark Selby or Stephen Maguire v Judd Trump or Kyren Wilson.(n)

programme.title: Panorama
programme.desc: The UK fast-food industry is booming, with UK consumers spending more than £10 billion a year on takeaway food, with the online market being dominated by giants like JustEat and Deliveroo. But what is the real cost of convenience? Tina Daheley lifts the lid on its secrets, revealing how planning laws are being subverted and food safety legislation flouted in the battle to secure custom.(n)

programme.title: Imagine
programme.sub-title: Imagine - Tracey Emin: Where Do You Draw the Line?
programme.desc: Alan Yentob follows the artist over the course of the last year to chart her creative process at work, and talks about her life to date and how she sees the rest of her career. Tracey discusses her troubled early years in Margate and the series of breakthroughs in the 1990s that saw her become a leading light of the Young British Artists, featuring career-defining work like My Bed and her embroidered tent Everyone I Have Ever Slept With 1963-1995. Contributors include Sir Nicholas Serota, Jay Jopling, Maria Balshaw and David Dawson.(n)

programme.title: This Is BBC Two
programme.desc: Preview of upcoming programmes from BBC Two.(n)

programme.title: All Over the Place: Asia
programme.desc: Featuring a Korean rocket festival and solar-powered supertrees in Singapore.(n)

programme.title: Wild & Weird
programme.desc: Naomi Wilkinson and Tim Warwood investigate odd auditory occurrences, including a man who collects worms by grunting, and a gang of prairie dogs doing a Mexican wave.(n)

programme.title: All Over the Workplace
programme.desc: Freya sees herself as a full-time professional footballer and Chitua wants to be a player before progressing to manager. They visit a professional football club where they are put through their paces by the coaches, then meet the manager to find out all about formations and tactics. Presented by Alex Riley.(n)

programme.title: Show Me What You're Made Of
programme.desc: Stacey Dooley presents as the five kids return to the south of England for a taste of some of the shift work done at night by thousands of people across the country. The kids are taken aback to discover that they are joining the cleaning team at a big bus garage in south London. It's hard physical work, and the shift goes on long into the night, requiring them to sweep, mop and wash each double-decker bus by hand. As the job goes on, the youngsters are shocked to discover what passengers have left behind for them to clean up.(n)

programme.title: The Dog Ate My Homework
programme.desc: Host Iain Stirling is joined by child team captains Joseph and Aqos and special guests Sam Nixon, Mark Rhodes, Charlie Baker and Yuriko Kotani who battle it out in a series of hilarious rounds and challenges.(n)

programme.title: Richard Hammond's Invisible Worlds
programme.desc: The Top Gear presenter concludes his investigation, revealing a miniature universe of activity lying just beyond the limits of the human eye. He learns how the gecko lizard is capable of defying gravity, and demonstrates how microscopic changes in ice crystals can cause devastating avalanches. Plus, he explores the infectious range of a sneeze.(n)

programme.title: Natural World
programme.desc: Award-winning writer Robert Macfarlane spends a year travelling around Essex to discover the variety of landscapes and wildlife in the county. During his journey he visits desolate beaches and wild woods, sees huge flocks of red knot over the Thames, and encounters an array of animals including peregrine falcons, water voles, deer, barn owls and seals.(n)

programme.title: Homes Under the Hammer
programme.desc: Martin Roberts, Martel Maxwell and Dion Dublin follow the progress of a three-bedroom flat in Epsom, Surrey, a Wolverhampton house and a bungalow in the Cornish village of Ashton.(n)

programme.title: Food & Drink
programme.desc: Chef Gennaro Contaldo joins Michel Roux Jr in the kitchen to create an authentic lasagne with focaccia from scratch, while Kate Goodman offers a guide to choosing the right Italian red wine to make the perfect match. Great British Menu judge and restaurateur Oliver Peyton joins them for a debate on whether people should care more about where their food comes from.(n)

programme.title: Best Bakes Ever
programme.desc: In light of Britain's baking obsession, actress and cake expert Jane Asher presents a selection of recipes from television chefs, including James Martin, Mary Berry, Paul Hollywood, the Hairy Bikers, Raymond Blanc, Nigella Lawson, Tom Kerridge, Lorraine Pascale and Rachel Khoo.(n)

programme.title: Money for Nothing
programme.desc: Sarah Moore and her team revamp a pair of brown atomic chairs with the help of upholsterer Anthony Devine, and later find a mid-century hall unit that needs bringing up to date.(n)

programme.title: Back in Time for School
programme.desc: The time-travelling documentary reaches the post-Second World War years, when a revolution in education saw children separated into one of three schools - grammars, secondary moderns and technical. The volunteer pupils attend grammar, representing the one in four children who won a coveted place by passing the 11-plus exam. Here, they delve into teachings on sex education, cycling proficiency, the Coronation of Queen Elizabeth II in 1953 and rising incomes in the mid-1950s as well as debates among boys and girls on fighting for your country.(n)

programme.title: Tennis: Australian Open
programme.sub-title: Tennis: Australian Open Highlights: 2019 Day Six
programme.desc: Kat Downes presents action from day six of the opening Grand Slam tournament of the year, which takes place at Melbourne Park, and featured the latest third-round matches. Eventual men's singles champion Roger Federer sailed through to the last 16 with a straight-sets victory over Richard Gasquet at this stage last year, but women's top seed Simona Halep survived a much tougher test, defeating Lauren Davis in a match that lasted a remarkable three hours and 45 minutes.(n)

programme.title: Live Snooker: The Masters
programme.desc: Further coverage of the opening semi-final, played over the best of 11 frames on day seven at Alexandra Palace in London. The victorious player will have the opportunity to win the first Triple Crown title of the year and a first prize of £200,000 in tomorrow's final.(n)

programme.title: Cities: Nature's New Wild
programme.desc: Animals displaced from their habitats by human expansion, including elephants in Sri Lanka and capuchin monkeys on the Pacific coast of Costa Rica. The programme also examines situations where humans have learned to live alongside their animal neighbours, including a heron that has been visiting an Amsterdam house twice a day for 17 years and a project to preserve manatees in Florida that has saved them from being an endangered species. Last in the series.(n)

programme.title: Getaways
programme.desc: New series. Return of the programme exploring holiday destinations that can be travelled to directly from Ireland. Vogue Williams and Tommy Bowe visit Seattle in the US state of Washington and Joe Lindsay visits Dungarvan in Co Waterford.(n)

programme.title: Live Snooker: The Masters
programme.desc: Coverage of the second semi-final, played over the best of 11 frames on day seven at Alexandra Palace in London. Despite being an invitational event, this tournament is considered one of the more prestigious on the snooker calendar, and with the winner set to claim a cheque for £200,000, both of the players in this contest will be eager to progress to tomorrow's final. Kyren Wilson produced one of the most memorable comebacks in Masters history at this stage last year, overcoming a 5-2 deficit against Judd Trump to prevail 6-5 and become the first player born in the 1990s to reach a Triple Crown final. Though defeating Mark Allen in the final proved to be a bridge too far, Wilson has gone from strength to strength since his run here, establishing himself in the world's top 10.(n)

programme.title: Stockholm, My Love
programme.desc: Premiere. A Swedish architect travels through Stockholm on a journey of recovery to find peace and understanding from something bad that happened to her exactly a year earlier. Drama, starring Neneh Cherry, marking the fiction debut for director Mark Cousins.(n)

programme.desc: Judd Trump v Kyren Wilson. Extended highlights of the first-round match on the fourth day at Alexandra Palace in London.

programme.desc: Footage of animals that have made their homes in urban environments around the world. Featuring huge colonies of bats in Adelaide, smooth-coated otters at home in Singapore, and reticulated pythons living on the streets of Bangkok. Narrated by Daniel Kaluuya.

programme.desc: New series. The return of the programme celebrating inspirational farming families and the rural events where they showcase their hard work. programme.desc: Michael Portillo starts the next leg of his journey in the Acadian fishing village of Neguac, New Brunswick, where he learns how to farm sea oysters, before investigating why the French-speaking Acadians were expelled by the British from lands they had occupied further south. Boarding the night sleeper for the next 400 miles, he heads for Quebec City. With its narrow streets and flights of steps, and a hotel modelled on a 16th-century chateau, the city was the heart of New France and reminds Michael of Paris. However, its national dish leaves him cold.

programme.title: Unforgotten
programme.desc: Cassie and Sunny go in search of Hayley's family as the press begin to take an interest in the story. programme.title: Time Team

programme.sub-title: Radcot, Oxfordshire: Anarchy in the UK
programme.desc: Tony Robinson and the team embark on a dig in a field beside the Thames in Oxfordshire. As the dig gets under way, evidence of a large medieval building is uncovered, but it becomes apparent the site is more complex than first imagined.
